50|$|<b>Chromium</b> <b>trioxide</b> and chromic acids {{are strong}} oxidisers and may react violently if mixed with easily oxidisable organic substances. Fires or explosions may result.|$|E
50|$|Cyclohexanone can be {{prepared}} from cyclohexanol by oxidation with <b>chromium</b> <b>trioxide</b> (Jones oxidation). An alternative method utilizes the safer and more readily available oxidant sodium hypochlorite.|$|E
50|$|In the laboratory, {{naphthoquinone}} can {{be produced}} by the oxidation {{of a variety of}} naphthalene compounds. An inexpensive route involves oxidation of naphthalene with <b>chromium</b> <b>trioxide.</b>|$|E
50|$|Telluric acid {{is formed}} by the {{oxidation}} of tellurium or tellurium dioxide with a powerful oxidising agent such as hydrogen peroxide, <b>chromium</b> <b>trioxide</b> or sodium peroxide.|$|E
